# Ghadir Khumm

**Ghadīr Khumm** ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): غَدِير خُمّ) was a gathering of [Muslims](/Muslims) to attend a sermon delivered by the [Islamic prophet](/Prophets_and_messengers_in_Islam) [Muhammad](/Muhammad) on 16 March 632 [CE](/Common_Era). The gathering is said to have taken place by the ghadir ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): غَدِير, [lit.](/Literal_translation)&#8201; 'pool') in the [wadi](/Wadi) ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): وَادِي, [lit.](/Literal_translation)&#8201; 'valley') of Khumm, located near the then settlement of [al‑Juhfa](/Rabigh) on the path between [Mecca](/Mecca) and [Medina](/Medina), where Muhammad halted the large [caravan](/Caravan_(travellers)) of Muslims who had accompanied him in the [Farewell Pilgrimage](/Farewell_Pilgrimage), his only [Hajj](/Hajj) ritual.

In the sermon, made shortly before his death in June 632, Muhammad made a declaration in favor of [Ali ibn Abi Talib](/Ali_ibn_Abi_Talib), his cousin and son‑in‑law, by saying: "He whose [mawla](/Mawla) I am, Ali is his mawla " ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): من كنت مولاه فهذا علي مولاه). [Mawla](/Mawla) ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): مولاه) is a [polysemous](/Polysemous) [Arabic](/Arabic) word, which can mean 'patron', 'master', 'leader', or 'friend', depending on its context. [Shi'a Muslims](/Shia_Islam) believe this sermon to be a clear designation of Ali to lead the Muslim community after Muhammad and celebrate the anniversary of the event as [Eid al‑Ghadir](/Eid_al‑Ghadir). The [Sunni](/Sunni_Islam) community meanwhile regards the declaration as a simple affirmation of Muhammad's esteem for Ali.

---

## Etymology

**Ghadir Khumm** refers both to the gathering of Muslims for Muhammad's sermon and its location, which was a pond ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): غَدِير, [romanized](/Romanization_of_Arabic):&#160; ghadir ) fed by a nearby spring in a [wadi](/Wadi) known as Khumm, situated between the cities of [Mecca](/Mecca) and [Medina](/Medina). &#91;1&#93; The pond was located near the settlement of [al‑Juhfa](/Rabigh), &#91;2&#93; a strategic trijunction where routes from Medina, [Egypt](/Egypt_(Roman_province)), and [Iraq](/Lower_Mesopotamia) intersected. &#91;3&#93;

The word **khumm** ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): خُم) has been translated as 'deceiver', and the valley was so named because the water of its pond was saline and unfit for consumption. &#91;4&#93; At the time of the event, the original inhabitants of the region, namely, the [Banu Khuza'a](/Banu_Khuza%27a) and the [Banu Kinana](/Banu_Kinanah) tribes, had already abandoned the area due to its poor pasturage and harsh climate. &#91;1&#93; Before Muhammad's address there, the location was likely never used as a caravan stop. &#91;5&#93; In [Shia](/Shia_Islam) sources, the harsh environment of Ghadir Khumm is seen as emphasizing the urgency of Muhammad's divine task as he sought the largest audience for his address before the pilgrims parted ways. &#91;6&#93;

