## Background

See also: [Farewell Pilgrimage](/Farewell_Pilgrimage)

Ten years after [Muhammad's migration](/Hegira) to [Medina](/Medina) and on the last days of [Dhu al‑Qadah](/Dhu_al‑Qadah), Muhammad performed the [Hajj](/Hajj) rituals in Mecca shortly before his death in 632 [CE](/Common_Era). &#91;7&#93; This Hajj ceremony has become known as the [Farewell Pilgrimage](/Farewell_Pilgrimage). &#91;7&#93; In a sermon in Mecca (at [Mount Arafat](/Mount_Arafat)), &#91;8&#93; and possibly again at the Ghadir Khumm, &#91;1&#93; &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93; Muhammad alerted Muslims about his impending death. After the Hajj, he embarked on the return journey from Mecca to Medina, accompanied by an entourage of Muslims. The announcement at the Ghadir Khumm took place during the return journey among a congregation of these Muslims, &#91;2&#93; possibly numbering in the tens of thousands. &#91;11&#93;

The sermon

At Ghadir Khumm, Muhammad called the Muslim caravan to a halt ahead of the noon congregational prayer, before the pilgrims parted their ways, &#91;2&#93; and then asked for a dais to be raised. &#91;1&#93; After the prayer, &#91;12&#93; Muhammad delivered a sermon to a large number of Muslims in which he emphasized the importance of the [Qur'an](/Qur%27an) and his [ahl al‑bt](/Ahl_al‑Bait) ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): أهل البیت, lit. &#8201;'people of the house', his family). &#91;9&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;14&#93; &#91;1&#93; &#91;10&#93; His statement is widely reported by [Sunni](/Sunni_Islam) and Shia authorities, and the version that appears in [Musnad Ibn Hanbal](/Musnad_Ahmad_ibn_Hanbal) , a canonical Sunni collection of hadiths, reads:

> I left among you two treasures which, if you cling to them, you shall not be led into error after me. One of them is greater than the other: The book of God, which is a rope stretched from Heaven to Earth, and my progeny, my ahl al‑bt . These two shall not be parted until they return to the pool [of paradise] ( [kawthar](/Al‑Kawthar) ). &#91;13&#93;

Known as the hadith of the [thaqalyn](/Hadith_of_the_Two_Treasure), Muhammad might have repeated this statement on multiple occasions, &#91;13&#93; &#91;15&#93; and indeed several similar variants of this hadith can be found in Sunni and Shia sources alike. &#91;13&#93; For instance, the version that appears in [al‑Sunan al‑kubra](/As‑Sunan_al‑Kubra) , another canonical Sunni source, also includes the warning, "Be careful how you treat the two [treasures] after me." &#91;16&#93; Taking Ali by the hand, Muhammad then asked if he was not awla ( lit. &#8201;'have more authority over'&#32; or 'closer to') the believers than themselves, &#91;1&#93; &#91;17&#93; evidently a reference to verse 33:6 of the Qur'an. &#91;18&#93; &#91;19&#93; &#91;20&#93; When they affirmed, &#91;1&#93; he declared,

•  
"He whose mawla I am, Ali is his mawla ," ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): من كنت مولاه فعلي مولاه) &#91;2&#93; &#91;21&#93; &#91;12&#93; &#91;1&#93;

which is known as the hadith of the [walayah](/Walayah) ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): وَلاية, lit. &#8201;'spiritual authority') in Shia theology. &#91;9&#93; Muhammad might have repeated this sentence three or four more times, as reported in Musnad Ibn Hanbal . &#91;14&#93; &#91;16&#93; He then continued, "O God, befriend the friend of Ali and be the enemy of his enemy," according to some versions, &#91;9&#93; &#91;20&#93; including the Sunni [Shawahid al‑tanzil](/Shahahid_al‑Tanzil) and the Shia [Nahj al‑haqq](/Nahj_al‑Haqq) . &#91;22&#93; The Sunni scholars [Ibn Kathir](/Ibn_Kathir) ( d. &#8201;1373) and [Ahmad ibn Hanbal](/Ahmad_ibn_Hanbal) ( d. &#8201;855) relate that Muhammad's [companion](/Companions_of_the_Prophet) ['Umar](/Omar) congratulated Ali after the sermon and told him, "You have now become mawla of every faithful man and woman." &#91;23&#93; &#91;1&#93; &#91;24&#93;

