## Other literary references

Ali publicly referred to the Ghadir Khumm during his caliphate, here he is shown receiving the [pledge of allegiance](/Bay%27ah) in a manuscript by the [Ottoman](/Ottoman_Empire) [Sufi](/Sufism) writer and poet Lami'i, late sixteenth century

The Ghadir Khumm has also been preserved in the Arabic literature. &#91;1&#93; &#91;49&#93; &#91;9&#93; The earliest such instance is a disputed poem attributed to [Hassan ibn Thabit](/Hassan_ibn_Thabit) ( d. &#8201;674), &#91;31&#93; who accompanied Muhammad during the pilgrimage. &#91;31&#93; For instance, the poem is quoted by the prominent Shia theologian [al‑Mufid](/Al‑Shaykh_al‑Mufid) ( d. &#8201;1022). &#91;50&#93; The poem appears also in some other Shia and Sunni sources, according to the Islamicist [Husain M. Jafri](/Husain_Mohammad_Jafri) ( d. &#8201;2019). &#91;31&#93; Included in this poem is the verse, "Stand up, O Ali, for I find only you to be an imam and a guide after I [Muhammad] depart." &#91;18&#93; &#91;24&#93; &#91;51&#93; In regards to its authenticity, [Mohammad A. Amir‑Moezzi](/Mohammad_Ali_Amir‑Moezzi), another expert, does not find this attribution problematic, &#91;9&#93; while Jafri considers it highly improbable that these events would have passed unrecorded by Ibn Thabit, who was the "official poet‑reporter of Muhammad." &#91;31&#93; By contrast, the Islamicists [Josef Horovitz](/Josef_Horovitz) ( d. &#8201;1931) and [Ignác Goldziher](/Ign%C3%A1c_Goldziher) ( d. &#8201;1921) reject the veracity of this poem. &#91;31&#93; The Shia [al‑Kumayt ibn Zayd](/Al‑Kumayt_ibn_Zayd_al‑Asadi) ( d. &#8201;743) is another early poet who composed verses on the same theme. &#91;9&#93;

