## Historical references

On one occasion during his caliphate, Ali is known to have asked Muslims to come forward with their testimonies about the Ghadir Khumm. &#91;52&#93; &#91;53&#93; &#91;54&#93; In doing so, he may have publicly laid claim to a spiritual and political authority greater than others, particularly his predecessors. &#91;52&#93; &#91;54&#93; &#91;55&#93; Muhammad's statement at the Ghadir Khumm, "O God, befriend the friend of Ali and be the enemy of his enemy," was likely the standard formula for pledging allegiance at that time. &#91;56&#93; Indeed, Ali and his son [Hasan](/Hasan_ibn_Ali) both demanded a similar pledge from their supporters during their caliphates. &#91;57&#93; The hadith of the walayah is also cited by [Ammar ibn Yasir](/Ammar_ibn_Yasir), a companion of Muhammad, to support the legitimacy of Ali's caliphate in the account of the Shia historian [Ibn A'tham al‑Kufi](/Ibn_A%27tham_al‑Kufi) (ninth century) of the negotiations before the [Battle of Siffin](/Battle_of_Siffin) (657). This might be the earliest such reference in historical sources. &#91;58&#93;

