## Eid al‑Ghadir

•  
Main article: [Eid al‑Ghadir](/Eid_al‑Ghadir)

While 18 [Dhu al‑Hijjah](/Dhu_al‑Hijjah) is not a significant day on the Sunni calendar, Shia Muslims celebrate this day as the [Eid al‑Ghadir](/Eid_al‑Ghadir), the day on which Islam was completed as a religion by the appointment of Ali as Muhammad's successor. &#91;1&#93; &#91;9&#93;
In a hadith attributed to Muhammad recorded by [Ibn Babawayh](/Ibn_Babawayh), Muhammad considers Ghadir Khum to be the best and highest of the festivals of his [Ummah](/Ummah). Specific rituals for Eid al‑Ghadir have been narrated by Shia Imams. Fasting on Eid al‑Ghadir is one of the recommended and emphasized ones. &#91;85&#93;
Shias honor the holiday by making pilgrimages to the city of [Karbala](/Karbala) in [Iraq](/Iraq). &#91;1&#93; &#91;77&#93;

